spanGrp.span: ‘I would say that mister’s name is Juan.
Yís të í she je pekaga kie rö Juan
He was chased by a horse;
he came in through the people’s door.
Í mẽnẽũ kawáũ pe puerta jãrga
There he met a huge tiger;
Jeska í tënã'wã (_) nãmã tã'ĩ kablali mẽ
he locked himself in with it and could not come back out.
(_) Jie jẽk kötiá-wã je ra Í kötenã'-wã ka í kösaũ ĩã
He thought he could get out through a smal door.
Begetsá-ite í kösãũ-nẽ puerta yuliski jãrga
On the other side there was another tiger, which he had escaped from.
Í sũã'-ite jamĩ etayë nãmã e-gla kate (_) je yiga jie beteũ jie jẽk bráwã
A dog came out to bite him;
jie jẽk yasã' í sũã'-ra chichi desãũ-te jie kue-gẽ
and he told the dog to shut up.
Jie të í (_) shá chichi ĩã-nã “¡ba siwã' blöwã
“Don’t bark!” he was afraid of the tiger.
ka ba (_) anã” (_) Jie suar-gẽ je nãmã tã'ĩ kablali yiga
Sũã'-ite-ra pemina deu í wö mẽ e-gla
I would say her name is Juana.
Yís të í shenã' (_) pemina kie rö (hm) Juana
He told her “Be quiet and open the door for me!”
Je të je ĩã í shá-ite-nã “¡ba (m) siwã' blöwã Jũkö yöu-mĩ ba kö (m) s-ĩã”
He was afraid, Mr. Juan was terribly afraid.
Jie suar pekaga Juan suar tã'ĩ
He put his feet down to scold the dog, but the dog bit his pants’ hems.
Í klö jawã-te chichi jũñõ chichi të í kwá-wã í klökwöga
The lady saw him and fainted;
(_) Pemina jie sũã' pemina siwã' janã-mĩ bata inga
Then he was afraid that the tiger would stand up and harm him, devour him;
Tsinẽpa jie suar-gẽ-nã yö je (_) nãmã jẽk gugá jie jie ra jirö wablö (_) jie kötöwã
he saw that the tiger indeed rose but did not do anything to him;
sũã-'ite-ra í jẽk kagá tara ka í wã (m) jirö wanẽ (_)
Then the woman came to him and opened the door for him.
Jekepa pemina deu-nẽ í wö inga pemina të jũkö (_) jũkö yáu-mĩ ĩã
He passed the door, Juan passed through the door, Juana behind.
Í kau-mĩ jũkö Juan kau-mĩ jũkö jãrga Juana töinga
He went to the other house;
Jie mẽnẽũ köũ jũ (_) e-tka nã
she saw, she saw that he did not go further, he climber on a tree, he sat in a branch.
sũã-'ite-ra ka jeska í mẽnẽũ jamĩgweta sũã-'ite-ra Juan tkagou rö kal mẽ Í(m) kel kaljula nã
So Juana said to him, “Come down; come!”
Jeska Juana të shá ĩã „¡ba jẽk jawa-te Ba shkö-te“
But he would not listen to her.
He saw he had not died;
jie të í sũã ka jie dunẽwã
he saw that it had not caused him any harm.
jie të sũã' jirö jirö klabe ka je ĩã jie wanẽ mẽnẽbi
Then he told her with his hands that he was very happy.
jekueinga jie të shá jula wa ĩã-nã jie ksenã tã'ĩ
He got up to there and would do nothing more.’
je ra jeska jie degãũ jeska jie ka jirö ka wã jirö (m) wanẽ
